Preamble¶

This report will examine the delays in public transport in the city of Zurich, Switzerland, based on data collected in November 2016. The data, found at https://www.openml.org/d/40753, contains the time difference (delay) between scheduled departure and actual departure of each public transport vehicle - bus, tram or trolley - for the duration which this data concerns.

The data will be read from its location on the OpenML website and then pre-processed before being explored further with visualisations including box plots and density plots. Then using the tools in the Scikit learn module, predictive models will be created and tested. This will enable us to create predictions for whether the bus, tram or trolley will be significantly delayed or not.

Check for irrelevant or redundant features ¶

There are no incident identification labels that need removing. There are, though, identification numbers for lines and stops. The line number is a label for the line, or route, taken by the bus, tram or trolley. This is a useful feature for learning as it is necessary to distinguish between different lines. Some may be more prone to traffic congestion, and therefore long delays may be more likely on such lines. It should not be removed but kept as a categorical feature. Being a nominal categorical feature, it should be one-hot encoded. The stop ID (stop_id) could be treated similarily, though there are likely to be very many stops leading to an extremely large number of features created by one-hot encoding.

In [4]:
# Check number of stop IDs
zurich_delays['stop_id'].nunique()
Out[4]:
1530

It would be better if this number was smaller to reduce the problem of high dimensionality. However, feature selection will ensure only the most important features are used. If it turns out that the rate of significant delays at a certain stop is no different to the average, then the feature pertaining to that stop is unlikely to be included in the model.

The hour is redundant as the hour is already included in the 'dayminute' variable. Currently hours denotes the hours after midnight. For example, if hours equals 12 than the incident was at 12 hours after midnight (i.e. noon). But this would also be given as 720 (12 * 60 minutes = 720 minutes), plus minutes after the hour, in the 'dayminute' feature.

In [5]:
zurich_delays.drop(columns='hour', inplace=True)

The features of interest concerning day and time are the day of the week and the time of the day which are captured by 'weekday' and 'dayminute' respectively. The date - the 'time' feature - may also be useful for capturing seasonal variation.

In [6]:
zurich_delays['time'].unique()
Out[6]:
array(['2016-11-13 05:00:00', '2016-11-13 05:10:00',
       '2016-11-13 05:19:59', ..., '2016-11-05 04:40:00',
       '2016-11-05 04:30:00', '2016-11-06 01:20:00'], dtype=object)

The observations appear to be all from November 2016. Hence no seasonal variation will be captured by this feature. It can be removed.

In [7]:
zurich_delays.drop(columns='time', inplace=True)

Out[8]:

       1.1, 1.6])

There are other values for precipitation so this feature is not constant. So it should not be removed.

Numerically encode categorical features ¶

As mentioned earlier, the line number and stop ID need to be one-hot encoded. The vehicle type and weekday are also categorical features that needs to be numerically encoded with one-hot encoding. (The weekday, while a number, denotes a day of the week. One day cannot be considered to be "twice as much" or "three times as much" as another day of the week.)

Furthermore, the direction is another categorical feature. Presuming only two directions, this can be encoded in binary fashion as 1 or 0.

In [15]:
# Check direction feature 
zurich_delays['direction'].unique()
Out[15]:
array([1, 2], dtype=int64)

As expected the direction is binary. Currently it has values of either 1 or 2. These will be changed to 0 and 1 respectively.

In [16]:
zurich_delays['direction']=np.where(zurich_delays['direction']==1,0,1)

In order to one-hot encode the stop_id and weekday features, each will be changed to be of "object" type.

In [17]:
zurich_delays['stop_id']=zurich_delays['stop_id'].astype(object)
zurich_delays['weekday']=zurich_delays['weekday'].astype(object)

Now the other four categorical features - vehicle type, line number, week day and stop ID - will be one-hot encoded.

In [18]:
# One-hot encode categorical variables
zurich_delays=pd.get_dummies(zurich_delays)

Place features in correct order, sample, create separate arrays for target and descriptive features and scale descriptors ¶

The target column is usually placed on the right. We are interested in the delay in the bus, tram or trolley so 'delay' is the target feature. So 'delay' will be placed on the right.

In [19]:
# Put 'delay' column last
zurich_delays=zurich_delays[[col for col in zurich_delays.columns if col not in ['delay']]+['delay']]

The number of observations is extremely large. To make the process more manageable for the computer, a sample of 5000 will be taken to be used henceforth.

In [20]:
#Take a sample of size 5000
zurich_delays_smp=zurich_delays.sample(n=5000,random_state=200)

We need to define how late a service has to be in order to be classified as significantly delayed. I will classify all services delayed by more than four minutes (240 seconds) late as significantly delayed. I will create a new variable - which will be the target feature - to indicate whether the departure is significantly delayed or not based on this criterion.

In [21]:
zurich_delays_smp['significantly_delayed']=np.where(zurich_delays_smp['delay']>240,1,0)

The descriptive features and the target need to be separated and converted to numpy arrays because the Scikit-learn module which we will use to do predictive modelling is designed to work with numpy arrays not pandas data frames. Once this is done the descriptive features will be scaled, and pre-processing will be complete.

In [22]:
# Separate descriptive features and target and convert to numpy arrays
Data=zurich_delays_smp.drop(columns=['delay','significantly_delayed']).values
target=zurich_delays_smp['significantly_delayed'].values

# Scale descriptive features
from sklearn import preprocessing
Data=preprocessing.MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(Data)

Note the 'significantly delayed' feature is the target. The feature 'delay' is not the target nor a descriptive variable so it is not included in the numpy arrays that will be used for predictive modelling. It will, however, be of interest to visualise this delay is affected by the descriptive features.

Data Exploration and Visualisation ¶

We will now examine the data with visualisations to assist in understanding the relationship between various descriptive features and the delay in a given public transport departure.

In [23]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
%config InlineBackend.figure_format='retina'
plt.style.use("ggplot")

Before we look at the relationship between descriptive features and the delay it will be good to gain an understanding of the distribution of the delay.

A histogram is an excellent way to view the distribution of a single variable.

In [24]:
# Create a histogram of delays
zurich_delays_smp['delay'].plot(kind='hist', bins=100)
plt.xlim(-300,1000)
plt.title('Public transport: delay in departure from stops\nZurich November 2016')
plt.xlabel('delay (seconds)')
plt.show()

The delays are positively skewed. This makes sense as negative delays indicate that the bus, tram or trolley is early, and it is far more likely for public transport to be very late than very early. If a bus, for example, is running ahead of schedule, the driver can simply pause at a stop until the correct departure time. But if he is running late due to heavy traffic, the traffic and speed limits may not allow him to catch up the lost time.

We should also consider what proportion of public transport departures are significantly delayed. The pie chart below graphically illustrates this proportion.

In [25]:
df=zurich_delays_smp[['vehicle_type_Bus']+['vehicle_type_Tram']+['vehicle_type_Trolley']+['weekday_1']+['weekday_2']+['weekday_3']+['weekday_4']+['weekday_5']+['weekday_6']+['weekday_7']+['delay']+['significantly_delayed']]
df['significantly_delayed']=np.where(df['significantly_delayed']==1,'late','not late')
df['significantly_delayed'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.1f')
plt.ylabel(None)
plt.title('Services departing stop more than 4 mins late')
plt.show()

From the pie chart we can see that 4.4% of all arrivals/departures are more than four minutes late.

Delays by vehicle type ¶

It will be of interest to see how each mode of public transport - bus, tram or trolley - performs as regards punctuality. Side-by-side boxplots will enable us to compare the punctuality of the three modes of public transport, both in terms of central tendency as well as variation.

In [26]:
df['Vehicle type']=df['vehicle_type_Tram'].replace(1,'tram')
df['Vehicle type']=np.where(df['vehicle_type_Bus']==1,'bus', df['Vehicle type'])
df['Vehicle type']=np.where(df['vehicle_type_Trolley']==1,'trolley', df['Vehicle type'])
df.boxplot(column='delay', by = 'Vehicle type')
plt.title(None)
plt.xlabel(None)
plt.ylim(-170,330)
plt.ylabel('delay (seconds)')
plt.show()

It seems that the trams have the best performance with the lowest median delay and lowest variation in delay also. Buses appear to have a better performance than trolleys with a slightly lower median and also less variation.

Now we will look at each mode of pubic transport individually.

We can also compare performance on hot days with performance on cold days.

In [30]:
df['Temperature']=np.where(zurich_delays_smp['temp']<np.median(zurich_delays_smp['temp']),'cold','hot')
df[df['vehicle_type_Bus']==1].boxplot(column='delay', by = 'Temperature')
plt.title(None)
plt.xlabel(None)
plt.ylabel('delay (seconds)')
plt.ylim(-170, 330)
plt.show()

It seems that buses travel slightly closer to schedule on cold days than hot days, but the difference is very small. Perhaps less people go out on cold days and so there are less passengers, making it easier for drivers to stay on time. As the difference appears very small, some more analysis is worthwhile to judge whether it is significant.

In [31]:
mu1=np.round(np.mean(df['delay'][(df['vehicle_type_Bus']==1)&(df['Temperature']=='cold')]),3)
print("The mean of the bus delays in cold weather is "+str(mu1)+".")
mu2=np.round(np.mean(df['delay'][(df['vehicle_type_Bus']==1)&(df['Temperature']=='hot')]),3)
print("The mean of the bus delays in hot weather is "+str(mu2)+".")
print("The difference in means is "+str(np.round(max(mu1,mu2)-min(mu1,mu2),3))+".")
sdBus=np.round(np.sqrt(np.var(df['delay'][df['vehicle_type_Bus']==1])),3)
print("The standard deviation of the bus delays is "+str(sdBus)+".")

The mean of the bus delays in cold weather is 56.981.
The mean of the bus delays in hot weather is 75.052.
The difference in means is 18.071.
The standard deviation of the bus delays is 128.268.

The difference in much less than one standard deviation. So the difference cannot be claimed to be significant.

Predictive Modelling ¶

The affects of the vehicle type, the day of the week, temperature, time of day and direction on the delay in a public transport service at any given stop has been considered. Now these and the other features we have retained - such as stop ID and line number - will be used to create models predicting whether any given public transport departure in Zurich will be significantly delayed or not (using the standard of delays longer than four minutes being "significant delays"). Three models will be created, one with each of the following algorithms: k-nearest neighbours, naive Bayes and decision trees. Finally, these models will be evaluated for performance.

Because it is an important principle of machine learning that algorithms be tested on data used neither for training nor hyper-parameter fine-tuning, the data will be partitioned to create a separate test set.

In [44]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

Each of k-nearest neighbours, naive Bayes and decision trees will be used to fit a model for predicting whether a departure will be significantly delayed or not. To evaluate models, a metric for comparing models is required. As this is a classification problem with class imbalance as shown below - only a small portion of the departures are delayed by more than four minutes - the metric used will be the f1 score.

In [45]:

First the k-Nearest Neighbours algorithm will be fitted to predict whether a departure will be significantly delayed or not.

k-Nearest Neighbours ¶

Public transport services with similar features such as vehicle type, time of day, day of the week, etc. are more likely to share a similar delay. There may be certain combinations of feature values that are more prevalent in cases where the departure is delayed. Therefore a classifier that predicts a departure as either of two classes, significant delayed or not significantly delayed, base on the class of similar departures, may be a good classifier.

It may be that only some features are important in determining whether a departure is significantly delayed or not. To determine the most important features a random forest classifier will be used to determine the importance of each feature in providing information about the target. Then the features will be ranked in terms of their importance, and the most important 10, 20, 30 and 40 features will be used to classify the departures. By varying the number of neighbours from 1 to 7 and using both Manhattan and Euclidean metrics, as well as varying the number of features included in the model, the best combination can be found. A grid search will fit models for each combination and evaluate the f1 score so that the optimal algorithm hyperparameters and number of features can be found.

In [46]:
# Create a random forest feature selector
# create a class to use Random Forest Importances to select best features for making predictions
# credits to (Feature Ranking, 2019, Hyperparameter Tuning: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)) for below (start quote)
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

class RFIFeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    # class constructor
    def __init__(self, n_features_=10):
        self.n_features_ = n_features_
        self.fs_indices_ = None
    
    # override fit function
    def fit(self, X, y):
        model_rfi = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)
        model_rfi.fit(X,y)
        self.fs_indices_ = np.argsort(model_rfi.feature_importances_)[::-1][0:self.n_features_]
        return self
        
    # override the transform function
    def transform(self, X, y = None):
        return X[:, self.fs_indices_]
# (end quote)

Decision Tree ¶

Now a decision tree will be implemented. This will simply divide the observations based on the values of the descriptive features. So if for example, the time of day is higher than a certain threshold, then those observations will be placed into one group and the other observations into another group. These groups can then be split into smaller groups by dividing on a different feature or a different threshold of the same feature. The goal is to split the observations into purer groups in regards to the target so that the target can be predicted based on which group an observation is in. Each split is a node of the tree, and the final groups that are created are its leaves.

In [56]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

To find the best hyperparameters, a grid search will again be employed. This time the pipeline will allow the model to use up to 50 features.

Discussion ¶

Naive Bayes performed the worst of all three algorithms. The assumption of conditional independence is flawed in this situation. If a public transport departure was by a bus, then it cannot be by a tram. So those two variables - the feature vehicle_type_bus and vehicle_type_tram - are not independent. Also the line features are not independent of each other, neither are the stops, because if one line feature (e.g. line_number_4) has value 1, the others must be 0, and similarly for stops.

The decision tree algorithm performed best. So it may be the best model to choose if you live in Zurich and you want to predict whether the public transport service you wish to catch is going to be delayed. It also has the advantage over its closest rival, k-nearest neighbours, of being an eager learner which means that while it may take a while to train, once trained it will give predictions faster than a lazy learner like k-nearest neighbours.

The original data contained the 'delay' variable so this data set could be used to fit a regression problem, namely predicting the delay given the descriptive features. However, I chose to turn this into a classification problem in which the model was required to predict whether a departure would be delayed by more than four minutes or not. As a consequence, the models in this report will only give a binary answer to the question of whether the delay was longer than four minutes, they will not give a quantitative prediction as to how long the delay might be. But people may not mind their bus being merely one or two minutes late, but it becomes annoying and frustrating when there is a significant delay, and four minutes may be a good demarcation between being significantly delayed or not. However, sometimes a smaller delay can still be a problem; for example it may prevent a passenger from reaching a connecting service on time. Also if a service was early (negative delay) than that could be a problem also, and the models created here will be of no use in predicting whether a departure will be early.

Conclusion ¶

After pre-processing data on Zurich public transport delays, it was explored and plots were created which gave more understanding of the data. It was seen that trams are the most punctual form of public transport in Zurich, and that delays are worse on some weekdays than others.

Using the k-Nearest Neighbours, Naive Bayes and Decision Trees algorithms, models were created to predict whether a departure would be significantly delayed or not. For each algorithm, a variety of hyperparameters were used to see which created a model that would generalise well to other data. The algorithms were than tested using the best hyperparameters found. The performance of each was compared. It was found that the decision tree performed best.
